<header>
  <div class="hdr">
    <span class="hdr-icon" aria-hidden="true">üåø</span>
    <h1 data-k="site_title">Deftere Golle</h1>
    <p class="hdr-sub" data-k="site_subtitle">Health &amp; Farming Guide ‚Äî Northern Senegal</p>
    <div class="hdr-langs" aria-hidden="true"><span>English</span><span>Pulaar</span><span>Wolof</span><span>Fran√ßais</span></div>
  </div>
</header>

<main id="content">

<article class="chapter active" id="ch-duckweed" role="tabpanel">
  <div class="ch-hero c1"><div class="ch-hero-inner"><div><p class="ch-num" data-k="ch1_num">Chapter 1</p><h2 data-k="ch1_title">Duckweed</h2></div><span class="ch-icon" aria-hidden="true">ü¶Ü</span><p class="ch-intro" data-k="ch1_intro">Duckweed is a tiny green plant that floats on still water. It doubles in size every 2‚Äì3 days. Grow it in a container and feed it to your chickens, goats, and fish ‚Äî it has protein as rich as meat.</p></div></div>
  <div class="ch-body">
    <div class="needs-box"><h3 data-k="needs_heading">What You Need</h3><ul class="needs-list"><li data-k="ch1_n0">One large bucket or basin (at least 50 liters)</li><li data-k="ch1_n1">Clean water ‚Äî from a river, tap, or well</li><li data-k="ch1_n2">Duckweed starter ‚Äî collected from a calm river or pond</li><li data-k="ch1_n3">Diluted animal urine or manure water (1 part manure to 10 parts water)</li><li data-k="ch1_n4">A spot with partial shade ‚Äî not full midday sun</li></ul></div>
    <p class="sec-label" data-k="steps_heading">Steps ‚Äî What to Do</p>
    <div class="step"><div class="step-num">1</div><div class="step-main" data-k="ch1_s1">Fill your large bucket with clean water, leaving two hand-widths of space at the top.</div></div>
    <div class="step"><div class="step-num">2</div><div class="step-main" data-k="ch1_s2">Place a handful of duckweed from a river or pond into the bucket. Let it rest on top of the water.</div></div>
    <div class="step"><div class="step-num">3</div><div class="step-main" data-k="ch1_s3">Add fertilizer: 1 part animal manure water to 10 parts clean water. Stir gently. Do not add too much.</div></div>
    <div class="step"><div class="step-num">4</div><div class="step-main" data-k="ch1_s4">Place the bucket in partial shade. Duckweed needs light but dies in full hot midday sun.</div></div>
    <div class="step"><div class="step-num">5</div><div class="step-main" data-k="ch1_s5">Wait 5‚Äì7 days. The duckweed will spread to cover the surface. It has grown successfully.</div></div>
    <div class="step"><div class="step-num">6</div><div class="step-main" data-k="ch1_s6">Scoop out half the duckweed with your hands. Move it to a second bucket with fresh water. Now you have two growing containers.</div></div>
    <div class="step"><div class="step-num">7</div><div class="step-main" data-k="ch1_s7">Feed the harvested duckweed fresh to your chickens, goats, or fish immediately.</div></div>
    <div class="step"><div class="step-num">8</div><div class="step-main" data-k="ch1_s8">Repeat the harvest every 3‚Äì4 days. The cycle continues every month.</div></div>
    <div class="rem-box"><h3>‚≠ê <span data-k="remember_heading">Remember This</span></h3><div class="rem-items"><div class="rem-item" data-k="ch1_r0">Mix only 1 part manure to 10 parts water ‚Äî never more.</div><div class="rem-item" data-k="ch1_r1">Harvest half every 3‚Äì4 days to keep it growing.</div><div class="rem-item" data-k="ch1_r2">Keep in partial shade ‚Äî not full hot sun all day.</div></div></div>
  </div>
</article>

<article class="chapter" id="ch-moringa" role="tabpanel">
  <div class="ch-hero c2"><div class="ch-hero-inner"><div><p class="ch-num" data-k="ch2_num">Chapter 2</p><h2 data-k="ch2_title">Moringa (Nebeday)</h2></div><span class="ch-icon" aria-hidden="true">üå±</span><p class="ch-intro" data-k="ch2_intro">Nebeday grows throughout Fuuta Tooro. Its leaves contain more protein than eggs, more calcium than milk, and more Vitamin A than carrots. One spoonful of dried leaf powder per day fights malnutrition.</p></div></div>
  <div class="ch-body">
    <div class="needs-box"><h3 data-k="needs_heading">What You Need</h3><ul class="needs-list"><li data-k="ch2_n0">A moringa (nebeday) tree ‚Äî or a cutting to plant</li><li data-k="ch2_n1">Clean water for washing</li><li data-k="ch2_n2">A clean cloth or mat for drying</li><li data-k="ch2_n3">A shaded room or covered area ‚Äî NOT direct sun</li><li data-k="ch2_n4">A mortar and pestle for grinding the dried leaves</li></ul></div>
    <p class="sec-label" data-k="ch2_sec1">Part 1 ‚Äî Harvesting</p>
    <div class="step g"><div class="step-num">1</div><div class="step-main" data-k="ch2_s1">Choose tender young leaves from the upper branches. These are the most nutritious.</div></div>
    <div class="step g"><div class="step-num">2</div><div class="step-main" data-k="ch2_s2">Pull leaves gently with your fingers. Do not damage the tree's main branches. Leave the stem to grow more leaves.</div></div>
    <div class="step g"><div class="step-num">3</div><div class="step-main" data-k="ch2_s3">Wash the leaves in clean water to remove dust and dirt.</div></div>
    <p class="sec-label" data-k="ch2_sec2">Part 2 ‚Äî Drying (Critical Step)</p>
    <div class="warn-box"><span class="warn-icon" aria-hidden="true">‚ö†Ô∏è</span><p data-k="ch2_warning">NEVER dry moringa leaves in direct hot sun. Sunlight destroys the vitamins and minerals. Always dry in shade.</p></div>
    <div class="step g"><div class="step-num">4</div><div class="step-main" data-k="ch2_s4">Spread leaves thin on a clean cloth in a shaded, well-ventilated place. No direct sun.</div></div>
    <div class="step g"><div class="step-num">5</div><div class="step-main" data-k="ch2_s5">Turn the leaves each day. After 2‚Äì3 days they will crumble between your fingers. They are dry and ready.</div></div>
    <div class="step g"><div class="step-num">6</div><div class="step-main" data-k="ch2_s6">Pound the dry leaves into fine powder using your mortar and pestle. Sieve out the stems.</div></div>
    <p class="sec-label" data-k="ch2_sec3">Part 3 ‚Äî Using the Powder</p>
    <div class="step g"><div class="step-num">7</div><div class="step-main" data-k="ch2_s7">Add one heaped spoonful to your sauce or child's porridge every single day.</div></div>
    <div class="step g"><div class="step-num">8</div><div class="step-main" data-k="ch2_s8">Add the powder AFTER the sauce has come off the fire. Heat destroys the nutrients. Stir in after cooking.</div></div>
    <div class="rem-box"><h3>‚≠ê <span data-k="remember_heading">Remember This</span></h3><div class="rem-items"><div class="rem-item" data-k="ch2_r0">Dry only in shade ‚Äî NEVER in direct sun.</div><div class="rem-item" data-k="ch2_r1">Add powder after cooking, not into boiling food.</div><div class="rem-item" data-k="ch2_r2">One spoonful per day for children, pregnant women, and elders.</div></div></div>
  </div>
</article>

<article class="chapter" id="ch-water" role="tabpanel">
  <div class="ch-hero c3"><div class="ch-hero-inner"><div><p class="ch-num" data-k="ch3_num">Chapter 3</p><h2 data-k="ch3_title">Safe Water &amp; ORS</h2></div><span class="ch-icon" aria-hidden="true">üíß</span><p class="ch-intro" data-k="ch3_intro">Water that looks clean can still carry illness. Unsafe water is a leading cause of child death. Three ways to make water safe ‚Äî plus how to make ORS, the life-saving drink for diarrhea.</p></div></div>
  <div class="ch-body">
    <p class="sec-label" data-k="ch3_sec1">Method 1 ‚Äî Boiling (Most Reliable)</p>
    <div class="step b"><div class="step-num">1</div><div class="step-main" data-k="ch3_b1">Pour water into a clean pot.</div></div>
    <div class="step b"><div class="step-num">2</div><div class="step-main" data-k="ch3_b2">Bring to a full rolling boil. Wait 1 full minute while it boils actively.</div></div>
    <div class="step b"><div class="step-num">3</div><div class="step-main" data-k="ch3_b3">Cover and let cool. Store in a clean covered container. Do not touch with dirty hands.</div></div>
    <hr class="div">
    <p class="sec-label" data-k="ch3_sec2">Method 2 ‚Äî Solar Disinfection (SODIS)</p>
    <div class="step b"><div class="step-num">1</div><div class="step-main" data-k="ch3_sodis1">Take a clean, clear plastic PET bottle. Fill completely to the top with water.</div></div>
    <div class="step b"><div class="step-num">2</div><div class="step-main" data-k="ch3_sodis2">Lay on a shiny surface (metal sheet or rooftop) in direct sunlight for 6‚Äì8 hours.</div></div>
    <div class="step b"><div class="step-num">3</div><div class="step-main" data-k="ch3_sodis3">If cloudy, leave for 2 full days (48 hours). UV light kills bacteria and parasites.</div></div>
    <hr class="div">
    <p class="sec-label" data-k="ch3_sec3">Method 3 ‚Äî Cloth Filtering</p>
    <div class="step b"><div class="step-num">1</div><div class="step-main" data-k="ch3_cloth1">Fold a clean cloth three times to make three layers.</div></div>
    <div class="step b"><div class="step-num">2</div><div class="step-main" data-k="ch3_cloth2">Pour water through the cloth into a clean container. This removes particles and sediment.</div></div>
    <div class="warn-box"><span class="warn-icon" aria-hidden="true">‚ö†Ô∏è</span><p data-k="ch3_cloth_warning">Cloth filtering alone does NOT make water safe. Always boil or SODIS as well.</p></div>
    <hr class="div">
    <p class="sec-label" data-k="ch3_sec4">ORS ‚Äî Life-Saving Drink for Diarrhea</p>
    <p style="font-size:.88rem;color:var(--txt2);margin-bottom:12px" data-k="ch3_ors_intro">Diarrhea removes water and salt from the body fast. It kills small children. ORS replaces what is lost.</p>
    <div class="ors-box"><h3 data-k="ors_title">ORS Recipe ‚Äî 1 Liter</h3><div class="ors-row"><div class="ors-item"><div class="ors-amt">1L</div><div class="ors-ing" data-k="ors_water">Boiled clean water</div></div><span class="ors-plus" aria-hidden="true">+</span><div class="ors-item"><div class="ors-amt">6</div><div class="ors-ing" data-k="ors_sugar">Teaspoons sugar</div></div><span class="ors-plus" aria-hidden="true">+</span><div class="ors-item"><div class="ors-amt">¬Ω</div><div class="ors-ing" data-k="ors_salt">Teaspoon salt</div></div></div><p class="ors-note" data-k="ors_mix">Mix well. Give small sips often. Make fresh every 24 hours.</p></div>
    <div class="warn-box"><span class="warn-icon" aria-hidden="true">üè•</span><p data-k="ch3_clinic_warning">Go to clinic immediately if: sunken eyes, no tears when crying, cannot drink, blood in stool, or diarrhea continues 2+ days.</p></div>
    <div class="rem-box"><h3>‚≠ê <span data-k="remember_heading">Remember This</span></h3><div class="rem-items"><div class="rem-item" data-k="ch3_r0">Boiling water is the most reliable purification method.</div><div class="rem-item" data-k="ch3_r1">ORS: 1 liter water + 6 teaspoons sugar + ¬Ω teaspoon salt.</div><div class="rem-item" data-k="ch3_r2">Sunken eyes, no tears, no urination = go to clinic immediately.</div></div></div>
  </div>
</article>

<article class="chapter" id="ch-soil" role="tabpanel">
  <div class="ch-hero c4"><div class="ch-hero-inner"><div><p class="ch-num" data-k="ch4_num">Chapter 4</p><h2 data-k="ch4_title">Soil, Compost &amp; Rotation</h2></div><span class="ch-icon" aria-hidden="true">ü™±</span><p class="ch-intro" data-k="ch4_intro">Tired soil gives small harvests. You can restore it without buying anything. Compost feeds the soil with what you already throw away. Zai pits catch rain. Crop rotation lets the land rest and recover.</p></div></div>
  <div class="ch-body">
    <p class="sec-label" data-k="ch4_signs_heading">Signs Your Soil Is Tired</p>
    <ul class="needs-list" style="margin-bottom:16px"><li data-k="ch4_sign0">Soil cracks and hardens after rain</li><li data-k="ch4_sign1">Seeds sprout but plants do not grow tall</li><li data-k="ch4_sign2">Harvests get smaller every year</li><li data-k="ch4_sign3">Soil looks pale or grey, not dark</li></ul>
    <p class="sec-label" data-k="ch4_sec1">Part 1 ‚Äî Making Compost</p>
    <div class="needs-box"><h3 data-k="needs_heading">What You Need</h3><ul class="needs-list"><li data-k="ch4_n0">Greens: fresh leaves, kitchen scraps, plant cuttings</li><li data-k="ch4_n1">Browns: dry stalks, old harvest stems, wood ash</li><li data-k="ch4_n2">Animal droppings (goat, chicken)</li><li data-k="ch4_n3">A little water</li><li data-k="ch4_n4">A compost pit or enclosed area ‚Äî 1m √ó 1m</li></ul></div>
    <div class="step o"><div class="step-num">1</div><div class="step-main" data-k="ch4_s1">Dig a compost pit near your field ‚Äî about 1 meter √ó 1 meter. Or make a pile on the surface.</div></div>
    <div class="step o"><div class="step-num">2</div><div class="step-main" data-k="ch4_s2">Add alternating layers: browns first, then greens, then animal droppings. Repeat.</div></div>
    <div class="step o"><div class="step-num">3</div><div class="step-main" data-k="ch4_s3">Sprinkle water to keep the pile damp but not soaking wet.</div></div>
    <div class="step o"><div class="step-num">4</div><div class="step-main" data-k="ch4_s4">Turn and mix the pile every two weeks. Turning helps it rot faster.</div></div>
    <div class="step o"><div class="step-num">5</div><div class="step-main" data-k="ch4_s5">After 3‚Äì4 months, the compost is dark, rich, crumbles like soil. Mix into your field before planting.</div></div>
    <hr class="div">
    <p class="sec-label" data-k="ch4_sec2">Part 2 ‚Äî Zai Pits</p>
    <div class="step o"><div class="step-num">1</div><div class="step-main" data-k="ch4_zai1">Before planting, make small holes in the soil ‚Äî about 30 cm apart across your field.</div></div>
    <div class="step o"><div class="step-num">2</div><div class="step-main" data-k="ch4_zai2">Add a small handful of compost or animal droppings into each hole.</div></div>
    <div class="step o"><div class="step-num">3</div><div class="step-main" data-k="ch4_zai3">Plant your seed in the hole. When rain falls, it collects in the hole instead of running away.</div></div>
    <hr class="div">
    <p class="sec-label" data-k="ch4_sec3">Part 3 ‚Äî Crop Rotation</p>
    <div class="step o"><div class="step-num">1</div><div class="step-main" data-k="ch4_rot1">Do not plant millet or sorghum in the same field every year. The soil becomes exhausted.</div></div>
    <div class="step o"><div class="step-num">2</div><div class="step-main" data-k="ch4_rot2">After millet, plant cowpea (ni√©b√©). Cowpea puts nitrogen back into the soil naturally.</div></div>
    <div class="step o"><div class="step-num">3</div><div class="step-main" data-k="ch4_rot3">After harvest, mix the cowpea stalks into the soil. They restore and clean the land.</div></div>
    <div class="rem-box"><h3>‚≠ê <span data-k="remember_heading">Remember This</span></h3><div class="rem-items"><div class="rem-item" data-k="ch4_r0">Compost is made from what you already throw away ‚Äî nothing to buy.</div><div class="rem-item" data-k="ch4_r1">Zai pits catch rain so it doesn't run away from your plants.</div><div class="rem-item" data-k="ch4_r2">Rotate: millet ‚Üí cowpea ‚Üí millet. The soil will recover.</div></div></div>
  </div>
</article>

<article class="chapter" id="ch-health" role="tabpanel">
  <div class="ch-hero c5"><div class="ch-hero-inner"><div><p class="ch-num" data-k="ch5_num">Chapter 5</p><h2 data-k="ch5_title">Essential Health Basics</h2></div><span class="ch-icon" aria-hidden="true">‚ù§Ô∏è</span><p class="ch-intro" data-k="ch5_intro">Five health topics that save the most lives ‚Äî and cost nothing but knowledge. Handwashing, malaria, pregnancy danger signs, wound care, and child growth tracking.</p></div></div>
  <div class="ch-body">
    <div class="hc-grid">
      <div class="hc hc-hands"><div class="hc-head"><span class="hc-icon" aria-hidden="true">üßº</span><h3 data-k="hc1_title">The 5 Critical Times to Wash Hands</h3></div><div class="hc-body"><p style="font-size:.82rem;color:var(--txt3);margin-bottom:9px" data-k="hc1_intro">Most diarrhea and respiratory disease is transmitted by dirty hands. These 5 moments matter most.</p><ul><li data-k="hc1_l0">After using the toilet or latrine</li><li data-k="hc1_l1">After cleaning a child who has defecated</li><li data-k="hc1_l2">Before preparing food</li><li data-k="hc1_l3">Before eating</li><li data-k="hc1_l4">Before breastfeeding or feeding a child</li></ul><p class="hc-note" data-k="hc1_note">Wash with soap and water for 20 seconds. If no soap, use ash ‚Äî it works.</p></div></div>
      <div class="hc hc-malaria"><div class="hc-head"><span class="hc-icon" aria-hidden="true">ü¶ü</span><h3 data-k="hc2_title">Malaria ‚Äî Prevention &amp; Signs</h3></div><div class="hc-body"><p class="hc-sublabel" data-k="hc2_prevent_label">Prevention:</p><ul><li data-k="hc2_p0">Sleep under a treated mosquito net every night ‚Äî especially children and pregnant women</li><li data-k="hc2_p1">Empty standing water near home every week</li><li data-k="hc2_p2">Drain stagnant pools within 100 meters of your home</li><li data-k="hc2_p3">Wear long sleeves after sunset when mosquitoes are most active</li></ul><p class="hc-sublabel red" data-k="hc2_signs_label">Danger signs ‚Äî go to clinic immediately:</p><ul><li data-k="hc2_s0">Fever with shaking or rigors (especially in a child)</li><li data-k="hc2_s1">Child is confused or cannot wake up normally</li><li data-k="hc2_s2">Fever lasts more than 24 hours without improvement</li><li data-k="hc2_s3">Vomiting and cannot keep fluids down</li></ul></div></div>
      <div class="hc hc-preg"><div class="hc-head"><span class="hc-icon" aria-hidden="true">ü§∞</span><h3 data-k="hc3_title">Pregnancy ‚Äî Danger Signs</h3></div><div class="hc-body"><p style="font-size:.82rem;color:var(--txt3);margin-bottom:9px" data-k="hc3_intro">Go to health center immediately ‚Äî do not wait ‚Äî if a pregnant woman shows any of these:</p><ul><li data-k="hc3_l0">Heavy bleeding from the vagina at any time during pregnancy</li><li data-k="hc3_l1">Severe headache or blurred vision (dangerous blood pressure)</li><li data-k="hc3_l2">Swelling of the face and hands (preeclampsia)</li><li data-k="hc3_l3">Baby has stopped moving for more than 12 hours</li><li data-k="hc3_l4">Water breaks before labor contractions begin</li><li data-k="hc3_l5">High fever during pregnancy</li><li data-k="hc3_l6">Labor lasting more than 12 hours without birth</li></ul><p class="hc-note" data-k="hc3_anc">Visit health center at least 4 times during pregnancy ‚Äî even if you feel well.</p></div></div>
      <div class="hc hc-wound"><div class="hc-head"><span class="hc-icon" aria-hidden="true">ü©π</span><h3 data-k="hc4_title">Wound Care Basics</h3></div><div class="hc-body"><ul><li data-k="hc4_l0">Clean every wound immediately with clean running water for 5 minutes</li><li data-k="hc4_l1">Remove dirt gently ‚Äî do not scrub hard</li><li data-k="hc4_l2">Cover with a clean cloth or bandage</li><li data-k="hc4_l3">Change the covering daily</li><li data-k="hc4_l4">Do NOT put soil, leaves, animal dung, or oil on a wound ‚Äî causes infection and tetanus</li></ul><p class="hc-sublabel red" data-k="hc4_go_label">Go to clinic if:</p><ul><li data-k="hc4_g0">Wound has red streaks spreading outward ‚Äî blood poisoning</li><li data-k="hc4_g1">Wound from an animal bite or deep puncture</li><li data-k="hc4_g2">Fever develops after a wound</li><li data-k="hc4_g3">Wound has pus or bad smell after 2 days</li></ul></div></div>
      <div class="hc hc-muac" style="grid-column:1/-1"><div class="hc-head"><span class="hc-icon" aria-hidden="true">üìè</span><h3 data-k="hc5_title">Child Growth ‚Äî MUAC Check</h3></div><div class="hc-body"><p style="font-size:.82rem;color:var(--txt3);margin-bottom:10px" data-k="hc5_intro">MUAC checks if a child aged 6 months to 5 years is malnourished. Measure the upper arm with a ribbon or string.</p><ul><li data-k="hc5_c0"><strong style="color:var(--green)">GREEN (above 12.5 cm)</strong> ‚Äî Child is well nourished. Continue good feeding.</li><li data-k="hc5_c1"><strong style="color:#CC8800">YELLOW (11.5‚Äì12.5 cm)</strong> ‚Äî Child at risk. Increase food variety. Add moringa powder daily.</li><li data-k="hc5_c2"><strong style="color:#CC3300">RED (below 11.5 cm)</strong> ‚Äî Severely malnourished. Go to health clinic immediately.</li></ul><p class="hc-note" data-k="hc5_note">Check your child's MUAC every month. A child not gaining weight needs help now, not later.</p></div></div>
    </div>
  </div>
</article>

</main>

<div id="offline-badge" role="status" aria-live="polite">üì¥ Offline ‚Äî saved content available</div>
<footer><p data-k="footer_text">This guide is for educational purposes. Always consult a qualified health worker for medical decisions.</p><p style="margin-top:5px;opacity:.7">Fuuta Tooro, Northern Senegal ¬∑ Pulaar ¬∑ Wolof ¬∑ Fran√ßais ¬∑ English</p></footer>

<script>

// translations.js ‚Äî Deftere Golle PWA
// Languages: English (en), Pulaar/Fuutanke (pu), Wolof (wo), French (fr)
// Note: Pulaar translations use Fuutanke dialect (Senegal River Valley)
// Wolof uses standard Senegalese Wolof orthography
// All translations verified against documented sources where available

window.TRANSLATIONS = {

  en: {
    lang_attr: "en",
    dir: "ltr",
    site_title: "Deftere Golle",
    site_subtitle: "Health & Farming Guide ‚Äî Northern Senegal",
    install_text: "üì≤ Save this guide for offline use ‚Äî works without internet",
    install_btn: "Install App",
    offline_badge: "üì¥ Offline ‚Äî saved content available",
    footer_text: "This guide is for educational purposes. Always consult a qualified health worker for medical decisions.",

    // Tabs
    tab_duckweed: "Duckweed",
    tab_moringa: "Moringa",
    tab_water: "Water",
    tab_soil: "Soil",
    tab_health: "Health",

    // Shared
    needs_heading: "What You Need",
    steps_heading: "Steps ‚Äî What to Do",
    remember_heading: "Remember This",

    // Chapter 1 ‚Äî Duckweed
    ch1_num: "Chapter 1",
    ch1_title: "Duckweed",
    ch1_intro: "Duckweed is a tiny green plant that floats on still water. It doubles in size every 2‚Äì3 days. Grow it in a container and feed it to your chickens, goats, and fish ‚Äî it has protein as rich as meat.",
    ch1_needs: [
      "One large bucket or basin (at least 50 liters)",
      "Clean water ‚Äî from a river, tap, or well",
      "Duckweed starter ‚Äî collected from a calm river or pond",
      "Diluted animal urine or manure water (1 part manure to 10 parts water)",
      "A spot with partial shade ‚Äî not full midday sun"
    ],
    ch1_s1: "Fill your large bucket with clean water, leaving two hand-widths of space at the top.",
    ch1_s2: "Place a handful of duckweed from a river or pond into the bucket. Let it rest on top of the water.",
    ch1_s3: "Add fertilizer: 1 part animal manure water to 10 parts clean water. Stir gently. Do not add too much ‚Äî it will smell and harm the plant.",
    ch1_s4: "Place the bucket in partial shade. Duckweed needs light but dies in full hot midday sun.",
    ch1_s5: "Wait 5‚Äì7 days. The duckweed will spread to cover the surface of the water. It has grown successfully.",
    ch1_s6: "Scoop out half the duckweed with your hands. Move that half to a second bucket with fresh water. Now you have two growing containers.",
    ch1_s7: "Feed the harvested duckweed fresh to your chickens, goats, or fish immediately. They will eat it readily.",
    ch1_s8: "Repeat the harvest every 3‚Äì4 days. The cycle continues every month without stopping.",
    ch1_remember: [
      "Mix only 1 part manure to 10 parts water ‚Äî never more.",
      "Harvest half every 3‚Äì4 days to keep it growing.",
      "Keep in partial shade ‚Äî not full hot sun all day."
    ],

    // Chapter 2 ‚Äî Moringa
    ch2_num: "Chapter 2",
    ch2_title: "Moringa (Nebeday)",
    ch2_intro: "Nebeday grows throughout Fuuta Tooro. Its leaves contain more protein than eggs, more calcium than milk, and more Vitamin A than carrots. One spoonful of dried leaf powder per day fights malnutrition in children, pregnant women, and elders.",
    ch2_needs: [
      "A moringa (nebeday) tree ‚Äî or a cutting to plant",
      "Clean water for washing",
      "A clean cloth or mat for drying",
      "A shaded room or covered area ‚Äî NOT direct sun",
      "A mortar and pestle for grinding the dried leaves"
    ],
    ch2_sec1: "Part 1 ‚Äî Harvesting",
    ch2_s1: "Choose tender young leaves from the upper branches. These are the most nutritious.",
    ch2_s2: "Pull leaves gently with your fingers. Do not cut or damage the tree's main branches. Leave the stem to grow more leaves.",
    ch2_s3: "Wash the leaves in clean water to remove dust and dirt.",
    ch2_sec2: "Part 2 ‚Äî Drying (Critical Step)",
    ch2_warning: "NEVER dry moringa leaves in direct hot sun. Sunlight destroys the vitamins and minerals. Always dry in shade.",
    ch2_s4: "Spread leaves thin on a clean cloth in a shaded, well-ventilated place. No direct sun.",
    ch2_s5: "Turn the leaves each day. After 2‚Äì3 days they will crumble between your fingers. They are dry and ready.",
    ch2_s6: "Pound the dry leaves into fine powder using your mortar and pestle. Sieve out the stems.",
    ch2_sec3: "Part 3 ‚Äî Using the Powder",
    ch2_s7: "Add one heaped spoonful to your sauce or child's porridge every single day.",
    ch2_s8: "Add the powder AFTER the sauce has come off the fire. Heat destroys the nutrients. Stir in after cooking.",
    ch2_remember: [
      "Dry only in shade ‚Äî NEVER in direct sun.",
      "Add powder after cooking, not into boiling food.",
      "One spoonful per day for children, pregnant women, and elders."
    ],

    // Chapter 3 ‚Äî Water
    ch3_num: "Chapter 3",
    ch3_title: "Safe Water & ORS",
    ch3_intro: "Water that looks clean can still carry illness. Unsafe water is a leading cause of child death. This chapter shows three ways to make water safe ‚Äî and how to make ORS, the life-saving drink that treats diarrhea.",
    ch3_sec1: "Method 1 ‚Äî Boiling (Most Reliable)",
    ch3_b1: "Pour water into a clean pot.",
    ch3_b2: "Bring to a full rolling boil. Wait 1 full minute while it boils actively.",
    ch3_b3: "Cover and let cool. Store in a clean covered container. Do not touch the water with dirty hands.",
    ch3_sec2: "Method 2 ‚Äî Solar Disinfection (SODIS)",
    ch3_sodis1: "Take a clean, clear plastic PET bottle (the type water or soft drinks come in). Fill completely to the top with water.",
    ch3_sodis2: "Lay the bottle on a shiny surface (a metal sheet or rooftop) in direct sunlight for 6‚Äì8 hours.",
    ch3_sodis3: "If the sky was cloudy, leave for 2 full days (48 hours). The UV light kills bacteria and parasites.",
    ch3_sec3: "Method 3 ‚Äî Cloth Filtering (For Cloudy Water)",
    ch3_cloth1: "Fold a clean cloth three times to make three layers.",
    ch3_cloth2: "Pour water through the cloth into a clean container. This removes large particles and sediment.",
    ch3_cloth_warning: "Cloth filtering alone does NOT make water safe to drink. Always boil or SODIS as well.",
    ch3_sec4: "ORS ‚Äî The Life-Saving Drink for Diarrhea",
    ch3_ors_intro: "Diarrhea removes water and salt from the body fast. It kills small children. ORS replaces what is lost. Make it exactly as shown.",
    ors_title: "ORS Recipe ‚Äî 1 Liter",
    ors_water: "Boiled clean water",
    ors_sugar: "Teaspoons sugar",
    ors_salt: "Teaspoon salt",
    ors_mix: "Mix well. Give small sips often. Make a fresh batch every 24 hours.",
    ch3_clinic_warning: "Go to the health clinic immediately if: the child has sunken eyes, no tears when crying, cannot drink, has blood in stool, or diarrhea continues more than 2 days.",
    ch3_remember: [
      "Boiling water is the most reliable purification method.",
      "ORS: 1 liter water + 6 teaspoons sugar + ¬Ω teaspoon salt.",
      "Sunken eyes, no tears, no urination = go to clinic immediately."
    ],

    // Chapter 4 ‚Äî Soil
    ch4_num: "Chapter 4",
    ch4_title: "Soil, Compost & Crop Rotation",
    ch4_intro: "Tired soil gives small harvests. You can restore it without buying anything. Compost feeds the soil with what you already throw away. Zai pits catch rain. Crop rotation lets the land rest and recover.",
    ch4_signs_heading: "Signs Your Soil Is Tired",
    ch4_signs: [
      "Soil cracks and hardens after rain",
      "Seeds sprout but plants do not grow tall",
      "Harvests get smaller every year",
      "Soil looks pale or grey, not dark"
    ],
    ch4_sec1: "Part 1 ‚Äî Making Compost",
    ch4_needs: [
      "Greens: fresh leaves, kitchen scraps, plant cuttings",
      "Browns: dry stalks, old harvest stems, wood ash",
      "Animal droppings (goat, chicken)",
      "A little water",
      "A compost pit or enclosed area ‚Äî 1m √ó 1m"
    ],
    ch4_s1: "Dig a compost pit near your field ‚Äî about 1 meter √ó 1 meter. Or make a pile on the surface.",
    ch4_s2: "Add alternating layers: browns first, then greens, then animal droppings. Repeat.",
    ch4_s3: "Sprinkle water to keep the pile damp but not soaking wet.",
    ch4_s4: "Turn and mix the pile every two weeks. Turning helps it rot faster.",
    ch4_s5: "After 3‚Äì4 months, the compost is dark, rich, and crumbles like soil. Mix it into your field before planting.",
    ch4_sec2: "Part 2 ‚Äî Zai Pits (Catching Rainwater)",
    ch4_zai1: "Before planting, make small holes in the soil ‚Äî about 30 cm apart across your field.",
    ch4_zai2: "Add a small handful of compost or animal droppings into each hole.",
    ch4_zai3: "Plant your seed in the hole. When rain falls, it collects in the hole instead of running away. This feeds the growing plant.",
    ch4_sec3: "Part 3 ‚Äî Crop Rotation",
    ch4_rot1: "Do not plant millet or sorghum in the same field every year. The soil becomes exhausted.",
    ch4_rot2: "After millet, plant cowpea (ni√©b√©) in that field. Cowpea puts nitrogen back into the soil naturally.",
    ch4_rot3: "After harvest, mix the cowpea stalks into the soil ‚Äî do not throw them away. They restore and clean the land.",
    ch4_remember: [
      "Compost is made from what you already throw away ‚Äî nothing to buy.",
      "Zai pits catch rain so it doesn't run away from your plants.",
      "Rotate: millet ‚Üí cowpea ‚Üí millet. The soil will recover."
    ],

    // Chapter 5 ‚Äî Health
    ch5_num: "Chapter 5",
    ch5_title: "Essential Health Basics",
    ch5_intro: "Five health topics that save the most lives ‚Äî and cost nothing but knowledge. Handwashing, malaria, pregnancy danger signs, wound care, and tracking your child's growth.",
    hc1_title: "The 5 Critical Times to Wash Hands",
    hc1_intro: "Most diarrhea and respiratory disease is transmitted by dirty hands. These 5 moments matter most ‚Äî all others are less critical.",
    hc1_list: [
      "After using the toilet or latrine",
      "After cleaning a child who has defecated",
      "Before preparing food",
      "Before eating",
      "Before breastfeeding or feeding a child"
    ],
    hc1_note: "Wash with soap and water for at least 20 seconds. If no soap, use ash ‚Äî it works.",
    hc2_title: "Malaria ‚Äî Prevention & Early Signs",
    hc2_prevent_label: "Prevention:",
    hc2_prevent: [
      "Sleep under a treated mosquito net every night ‚Äî especially children and pregnant women",
      "Empty all standing water near your home ‚Äî buckets, pots, puddles ‚Äî every week",
      "Drain or fill any stagnant pools within 100 meters of your home",
      "Wear long sleeves after sunset when mosquitoes are most active"
    ],
    hc2_signs_label: "Danger signs ‚Äî go to clinic immediately:",
    hc2_signs: [
      "Fever with shaking or rigors (especially in a child)",
      "Child is confused or cannot wake up normally",
      "Fever lasts more than 24 hours without improvement",
      "Vomiting and cannot keep fluids down"
    ],
    hc3_title: "Pregnancy ‚Äî Danger Signs",
    hc3_intro: "Go to the health center immediately ‚Äî do not wait ‚Äî if a pregnant woman shows any of these signs:",
    hc3_list: [
      "Heavy bleeding from the vagina at any time during pregnancy",
      "Severe headache or blurred vision (sign of dangerous blood pressure)",
      "Swelling of the face and hands (sign of preeclampsia)",
      "Baby has stopped moving for more than 12 hours",
      "Water breaks before labor contractions begin",
      "High fever during pregnancy",
      "Labor lasting more than 12 hours without birth"
    ],
    hc3_anc: "Visit the health center at least 4 times during pregnancy ‚Äî even if you feel well.",
    hc4_title: "Wound Care Basics",
    hc4_list: [
      "Clean every wound immediately with clean running water for 5 minutes",
      "Remove dirt and debris gently ‚Äî do not scrub hard",
      "Cover with a clean cloth or bandage",
      "Change the covering daily",
      "Do NOT put soil, leaves, animal dung, or oil on a wound ‚Äî this causes infection and tetanus"
    ],
    hc4_go_label: "Go to clinic if:",
    hc4_go: [
      "Wound has red streaks spreading outward ‚Äî this is blood poisoning",
      "Wound is from an animal bite or deep puncture",
      "Fever develops after a wound",
      "Wound has pus or bad smell after 2 days"
    ],
    hc5_title: "Child Growth ‚Äî MUAC Check",
    hc5_intro: "MUAC (Mid-Upper Arm Circumference) is the easiest way to check if a child aged 6 months to 5 years is malnourished. Measure the upper arm with a ribbon or string.",
    hc5_colors: [
      "<strong style='color:var(--earth-green)'>GREEN (above 12.5 cm)</strong> ‚Äî Child is well nourished. Continue good feeding.",
      "<strong style='color:#CC8800'>YELLOW (11.5‚Äì12.5 cm)</strong> ‚Äî Child is at risk. Increase food variety. Add moringa powder daily.",
      "<strong style='color:#CC3300'>RED (below 11.5 cm)</strong> ‚Äî Child is severely malnourished. Go to health clinic immediately."
    ],
    hc5_note: "Check your child's MUAC every month. A child who is not gaining weight needs help now, not later."
  },

